Below is an example of how you could set up a simulation:

1. Create a method called `runSimulation` which accepts a list of skins, the number of iterations (how many random tradeups you'd like to generate), and the top N most profitable tradeups you'd like to keep.

2. Create a `PriorityQueue` to store the top N most profitable tradeups, with a custom comparator to sort the tradeups based on profitability.

3. During each iteration, randomly generate a tradeup by selecting random skins from the input list and randomly assigning their wear in between the minimum and maximum wear values.

4. Calculate the profitability and other properties of the tradeup.

5. Add the tradeup to the priority queue, and remove the least profitable tradeup if the queue size exceeds N.

Here's a simple implementation:

```java
import java.util.*;

public class TradeupSimulator {
    public List<TradeUp> runSimulation(List<Skin> skinList, int numIterations, int topN) {
        PriorityQueue<TradeUp> mostProfitableTradeups = new PriorityQueue<>((t1, t2) -> (int) (t1.profitability - t2.profitability));

        for (int i = 0; i < numIterations; i++) {
            TradeUp tradeUp = new TradeUp();

            for (int j = 0; j < 10; j++) {
                // Randomly select a skin
                Skin skin = skinList.get(new Random().nextInt(skinList.size()));

                // Randomly assign a wear value in between the minimum and maximum wear
                float wear = skin.getMinWear() + new Random().nextFloat() * (skin.getMaxWear() - skin.getMinWear());

                // Create a copy of the skin with assigned wear value and price
                Skin selectedSkin = skin.withWear(wear);
                selectedSkin.setPrice(getPriceFromWear(wear));

                // Add the skin with assigned wear to the tradeup.
                tradeUp.addSkin(selectedSkin);
            }

            // Calculate tradeup properties (profit, cost, etc.) here
            calculateTradeupProperties(tradeUp);

            // Maintain the top N most profitable tradeups in the priority queue
            mostProfitableTradeups.offer(tradeUp);
            if (mostProfitableTradeups.size() > topN) {
                mostProfitableTradeups.poll();
            }
        }

        // Convert the priority queue to a list and return
        return new ArrayList<>(mostProfitableTradeups);
    }
}
```

This approach will generate a number of random tradeups and keep track of the most profitable ones. You can adjust the number of iterations and the top N tradeups to balance performance and accuracy.

Please note that this is a high-level implementation and you might need to adapt the code according to your specific classes and methods (such as `calculateTradeupProperties`, `withWear`, `getPriceFromWear`, etc.).

Comme vous souhaitez une approche plus précise en évitant de choisir des floats aléatoires ou le moyen entre le min et le max, vous pouvez opter pour une approche où vous subdivisez la plage de flottaison en plusieurs intervalles et vous générez des combinaisons pour chaque intervalle. Cela ajoutera plus de précision à votre simulation tout en ayant un contrôle sur le nombre de combinaisons générées.

Voici comment vous pouvez procéder :

1. Définissez un paramètre `numIntervals` pour diviser la plage de flottaison en plusieurs intervalles.

```java
int numIntervals = 5; // Par exemple
```

2. Lors de la création des combinaisons, au lieu de choisir le float moyen ou un random, divisez la plage en `numIntervals` intervalles, et générer une combinaison pour chaque intervalle.

Pour ce faire, modifiez la méthode `generateCombinations` pour prendre en compte les intervalles :

```java
private void generateCombinations(List<Skin> skinList, List<Skin> currentTradeUpList, int index, int numIntervals) {
    if (index == skinList.size()) {
        // Calculate the values for the current trade-up list using your TradeUps class methods
        // ...
        return;
    }

    Skin currentSkin = skinList.get(index);
    float wearStep = (currentSkin.getMaxWear() - currentSkin.getMinWear()) / numIntervals;
    for (int i = 0; i <= numIntervals; i++) {
        float wearValue = currentSkin.getMinWear() + i * wearStep;
        Skin skinWithWearValue = currentSkin.withWear(wearValue);
        skinWithWearValue.setPrice(getPriceFromWear(wearValue));
        currentTradeUpList.add(skinWithWearValue);
        generateCombinations(skinList, currentTradeUpList, index + 1, numIntervals);
        currentTradeUpList.remove(currentTradeUpList.size() - 1);
    }
}
```

